00:00:51.690 --> 00:00:57.100
OK, when we cool down fermions,
Lithium-6 and Boson sodiums

00:00:57.100 --> 00:00:59.440
we immediately
notice a difference.

00:00:59.440 --> 00:01:01.910
The sodium cloud shrink,
shrink, shrinks and forms

00:01:01.910 --> 00:01:04.190
a small Bose-Einstein
condensate,

00:01:04.190 --> 00:01:07.140
whereas the lithium
cloud stops to shrink

00:01:07.140 --> 00:01:09.850
when we reach the
degeneracy temperature.

00:01:09.850 --> 00:01:12.650
And, of course, you know
it's at low temperature.

00:01:12.650 --> 00:01:15.170
At high temperature the gases
have very similar behavior,

00:01:15.170 --> 00:01:19.190
but at low temperature they
look very, very different.

00:01:19.190 --> 00:01:22.200
And that can be
directly observed.

00:01:22.200 --> 00:01:26.220
We know that bosons do something
very special at low temperature

00:01:26.220 --> 00:01:28.460
and we talked a lot
about it in this course.

00:01:28.460 --> 00:01:30.616
Namely, they become
superfluid and form

00:01:30.616 --> 00:01:33.190
a Bose-Einstein
condensate, whereas,

00:01:33.190 --> 00:01:35.610
for single-component
fermions, there

00:01:35.610 --> 00:01:38.520
is some interesting physics
in form of Fermi sea,

00:01:38.520 --> 00:01:41.130
but nothing really special.

00:01:41.130 --> 00:01:44.830
So, in order to do something
more interesting with fermions

00:01:44.830 --> 00:01:47.010
you need two kinds of fermions.

00:01:47.010 --> 00:01:50.160
And two kinds of
fermions can form pairs.

00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:53.330
To think, for a moment, two
atoms can form a molecule

00:01:53.330 --> 00:01:56.750
and those Bosonic
pairs can condense

00:01:56.750 --> 00:02:01.320
into Bose-Einstein condensate
and becomes superfluid again.

00:02:01.320 --> 00:02:04.010
If that would be all to
Fermionic superfluidity

00:02:04.010 --> 00:02:05.980
I would be almost done
right now and would say,

00:02:05.980 --> 00:02:10.789
"OK a Bosonic atom is
a composite particle

00:02:10.789 --> 00:02:13.870
made of nuclei and
nucleus and electrons.

00:02:13.870 --> 00:02:16.540
Well, a bosonic molecule
is a composite particle,

00:02:16.540 --> 00:02:19.270
but in the end they
do both the same."

00:02:19.270 --> 00:02:21.310
But the special
things about fermions

00:02:21.310 --> 00:02:24.720
is there is another form of
pairing, which is much, much,

00:02:24.720 --> 00:02:26.310
weaker.

00:02:26.310 --> 00:02:29.690
And this is the form which
leads to superconductivity

00:02:29.690 --> 00:02:31.030
of electrons.

00:02:31.030 --> 00:02:32.890
It's Cooper pairing.

00:02:32.890 --> 00:02:35.370
And this is really
much more subtle

00:02:35.370 --> 00:02:38.170
because the pairs
are much larger

00:02:38.170 --> 00:02:41.640
than the inter-particle
separation.

00:02:41.640 --> 00:02:45.020
Now, in atomic physics,
we have a wonderful tool

00:02:45.020 --> 00:02:49.940
to study pairing because
atoms can form molecules,

00:02:49.940 --> 00:02:53.580
weakly bound molecules or
tightly bound molecules.

00:02:53.580 --> 00:02:55.850
And we can control
that in experiments

00:02:55.850 --> 00:02:57.790
with the Feshbach resonance.

00:02:57.790 --> 00:03:01.320
Assume you have two
atoms, which collide,

00:03:01.320 --> 00:03:03.390
and they can form a molecule.

00:03:03.390 --> 00:03:05.800
And if you apply
a magnetic field

00:03:05.800 --> 00:03:07.570
the two free atoms
and the molecule

00:03:07.570 --> 00:03:09.560
may have a different
Zeeman shift,

00:03:09.560 --> 00:03:12.730
and therefore, there
may be a level crossing.

00:03:12.730 --> 00:03:15.610
And this is called, as a
function of magnetic field,

00:03:15.610 --> 00:03:17.160
the Feshbach resonance.

00:03:17.160 --> 00:03:18.750
If the crossing isn't
crossing nothing

00:03:18.750 --> 00:03:20.750
happens because the two
configurations would not

00:03:20.750 --> 00:03:21.600
interact.

00:03:21.600 --> 00:03:25.670
So, physics happens when
there are interactions

00:03:25.670 --> 00:03:29.200
for some hyperfine
coupling, for instance,

00:03:29.200 --> 00:03:33.210
which takes the crossing
into an anti-crossing.

00:03:33.210 --> 00:03:35.120
And now you see the
following physics

00:03:35.120 --> 00:03:38.830
around this Feshbach resonance,
that we have two atoms here.

00:03:38.830 --> 00:03:41.950
Here, we have a stable molecule.

00:03:41.950 --> 00:03:44.430
And there are many, many more
molecular states down there,

00:03:44.430 --> 00:03:47.827
but for this restricted Hilbert
space this is the lowest state.

00:03:47.827 --> 00:03:48.785
It's a stable molecule.

00:03:51.980 --> 00:03:55.770
The atoms, if you compare the
solid line with a dashed line,

00:03:55.770 --> 00:03:59.384
attract each other because the
solid line has lower energy,

00:03:59.384 --> 00:04:01.550
whereas, on the other side
of the Feshbach resonance

00:04:01.550 --> 00:04:04.130
they repel each other.

00:04:04.130 --> 00:04:07.530
So therefore, if you
look at the scattering

00:04:07.530 --> 00:04:09.950
lengths of the normalized
force between atoms

00:04:09.950 --> 00:04:13.190
we find this disparity feature
around the Feshbach resonance,

00:04:13.190 --> 00:04:15.640
and atomic physics
wouldn't be the same

00:04:15.640 --> 00:04:17.320
without Feshbach resonances.

00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:20.720
We can now tune attractive
repulsive interactions.

00:04:20.720 --> 00:04:22.810
In a richer situation
there may also

00:04:22.810 --> 00:04:27.160
be Zero-crossings of the
scattering lengths, which

00:04:27.160 --> 00:04:29.940
allows us to realize
non-interacting systems

00:04:29.940 --> 00:04:31.620
and such.

00:04:31.620 --> 00:04:33.930
And Feshbach
resonances were first

00:04:33.930 --> 00:04:38.460
observed at MIT
some 15 years ago.

00:04:38.460 --> 00:04:41.130
So coming back to fermions.

00:04:41.130 --> 00:04:45.040
This Feshbach resonance gives
us something very interesting

00:04:45.040 --> 00:04:47.270
regarding to pairing.

00:04:47.270 --> 00:04:50.680
On that side where we
have stable molecules,

00:04:50.680 --> 00:04:53.930
those molecules are
bosons and those bosons

00:04:53.930 --> 00:04:58.000
form a Bose-Einstein
condensate of bound pairs.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:01.200
Over here, we have attraction.

00:05:01.200 --> 00:05:05.220
But the attraction is not strong
enough to form a bound state,

00:05:05.220 --> 00:05:07.160
at least two atoms
in vacuum would not

00:05:07.160 --> 00:05:08.720
find form a molecular state.

00:05:08.720 --> 00:05:10.860
The attraction is too weak.

00:05:10.860 --> 00:05:14.400
But we know from condensed
matter physics textbook

00:05:14.400 --> 00:05:18.100
if you have many fermions,
if you have a Fermi sea,

00:05:18.100 --> 00:05:20.780
then the Fermi sea
plus attraction

00:05:20.780 --> 00:05:24.060
equals BCS Cooper pairs.

00:05:24.060 --> 00:05:27.190
So now we have an opportunity,
by simply changing

00:05:27.190 --> 00:05:31.800
the magnetic field, to go from
real, strongly-bound pairs

00:05:31.800 --> 00:05:34.890
to weakly-bound pairs, and
eventually to Cooper pairs,

00:05:34.890 --> 00:05:37.640
which would not form
pairs in vacuum.

00:05:37.640 --> 00:05:39.630
And this is a kind
of physics, which

00:05:39.630 --> 00:05:42.840
was for the first time
explored with ultra cold atoms,

00:05:42.840 --> 00:05:44.731
in the BEC-BCS crossover.

00:05:44.731 --> 00:05:45.230
