00:20:43.520 --> 00:20:45.620
If you don't have
enough attraction

00:20:45.620 --> 00:20:49.150
it will never curve down and
become a normalizable state.

00:20:49.150 --> 00:20:52.500
Whereas, in 1D you do
not have the requirement

00:20:52.500 --> 00:20:55.210
that the wave function
if your 1D Schrodinger

00:20:55.210 --> 00:20:56.560
equation has a node.

00:20:56.560 --> 00:20:59.280
So you have the same equation,
the same infinitesimal

00:20:59.280 --> 00:21:02.980
potential, but the
radial equation

00:21:02.980 --> 00:21:06.410
has a different
boundary condition.

00:21:06.410 --> 00:21:08.540
So that's the difference.

00:21:08.540 --> 00:21:09.500
And that's important.

00:21:09.500 --> 00:21:12.380
It changes the
physics completely.

00:21:12.380 --> 00:21:13.450
OK.

00:21:13.450 --> 00:21:17.388
Now it looks very different and
it seems you have to-- Niki.

00:21:17.388 --> 00:21:19.660
AUDIENCE: What about 2D?

00:21:19.660 --> 00:21:22.025
PROFESSOR: Limiting case,
we come to that in a second.

00:21:22.025 --> 00:21:25.795
In 2D an infinitesimal
potential is still enough.

00:21:28.420 --> 00:21:31.530
Now I want to show you how you
can take care of all dimensions

00:21:31.530 --> 00:21:35.040
with one equation and not
solve three different equations

00:21:35.040 --> 00:21:37.730
with three different
kinetic energy terms.

00:21:37.730 --> 00:21:40.285
That goes as follows.

00:21:40.285 --> 00:21:42.410
Recognize that this is just
Schrodinger's equation,

00:21:42.410 --> 00:21:45.960
kinetic energy minus
energy equals potential.

00:21:45.960 --> 00:21:48.060
But now we can
Fourier transform it.

00:21:48.060 --> 00:21:50.280
And the nice thing about
Fourier transformation

00:21:50.280 --> 00:21:54.590
is that the second derivative,
spatial derivative,

00:21:54.590 --> 00:21:57.160
is simply q squared.

00:21:57.160 --> 00:22:05.000
So therefore, if you describe
now everything in Fourier

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:10.540
space, you have q squared
plus k squared times psi,

00:22:10.540 --> 00:22:14.450
but you divide by q
squared plus k squared.

00:22:14.450 --> 00:22:15.520
Here you have a product.

00:22:15.520 --> 00:22:17.700
The product turns
into convolution.

00:22:17.700 --> 00:22:20.580
Anyway, it may be not the most
familiar way you've seen it,

00:22:20.580 --> 00:22:24.510
but this is just Schrodinger's
equation in Fourier components.

00:22:24.510 --> 00:22:26.750
And now we want to
simplify that we

00:22:26.750 --> 00:22:28.440
have a short-range potential.

00:22:28.440 --> 00:22:31.970
So we assume we have a
short range potential.

00:22:31.970 --> 00:22:36.680
If you had a delta function,
the momentum components

00:22:36.680 --> 00:22:40.290
of the potential would
be constant for all R.

00:22:40.290 --> 00:22:42.440
But, we get into
something unphysical

00:22:42.440 --> 00:22:45.100
if you don't put in a cutoff,
so we put in a cutoff.

00:22:45.100 --> 00:22:47.050
But with that
cutoff, you can now

00:22:47.050 --> 00:22:49.630
re-write the
equation as follows.

00:22:49.630 --> 00:22:51.200
And now we want to do one thing.

00:22:51.200 --> 00:22:53.530
We want to integrate over q.

00:22:53.530 --> 00:22:57.210
Then on the right-hand side we
also have an integral over q.

00:22:57.210 --> 00:22:59.760
And then we divide
by the common factor.

00:22:59.760 --> 00:23:01.750
And what you get is this.

00:23:01.750 --> 00:23:03.910
I know I'm going fast,
but this is nothing else

00:23:03.910 --> 00:23:06.540
than re-writing Schrodinger's
equation for you.

00:23:06.540 --> 00:23:07.550
But now look at it.

00:23:10.260 --> 00:23:15.120
It has an integral
over all energies

00:23:15.120 --> 00:23:20.020
with the density of
states, or of E, of energy.

00:23:20.020 --> 00:23:22.130
E is k square.

00:23:22.130 --> 00:23:24.000
This is the energy
of the bound state,

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:26.180
and we want the bound state.

00:23:26.180 --> 00:23:27.900
And on the left
hand side we have

00:23:27.900 --> 00:23:30.370
our infinitesimal potential.

00:23:30.370 --> 00:23:32.210
And one thing is
clear, if you have

00:23:32.210 --> 00:23:34.600
an infinitesimal
potential, we can only

00:23:34.600 --> 00:23:37.490
get an infinitesimally
bound state.

00:23:37.490 --> 00:23:40.290
So now we do the following.

00:23:40.290 --> 00:23:53.450
If the left hand side
goes to 0, If you

00:23:53.450 --> 00:23:55.270
go to an infinitesimal
attraction,

00:23:55.270 --> 00:23:57.680
the left hand side diverges.

00:23:57.680 --> 00:24:01.020
And the question is now,
if the energy goes to 0,

00:24:01.020 --> 00:24:04.370
does the right hand
side diverge or not?

00:24:04.370 --> 00:24:07.500
In other words,
if this integral,

00:24:07.500 --> 00:24:11.320
where you said E equals
0, does not diverge,

00:24:11.320 --> 00:24:14.840
you cannot fulfill this
equation with an infinitesimal

00:24:14.840 --> 00:24:17.090
attraction in the
square of l potential.

00:24:17.090 --> 00:24:19.830
So therefore, the
condition for bound state

00:24:19.830 --> 00:24:24.490
is now that this expression
here with E equals 0, diverges.

00:24:28.430 --> 00:24:31.010
And this combines
now all the cases.

00:24:31.010 --> 00:24:33.340
And you have now an
integral equation,

00:24:33.340 --> 00:24:37.050
and you can now solve
it for infinitesimal V0.

00:24:37.050 --> 00:24:41.870
You can solve it, what is the
energy as a functional of V0?

00:24:41.870 --> 00:24:48.460
And in two dimensions, when the
density of states versus energy

00:24:48.460 --> 00:24:51.542
is constant, you have
the weakest divergence

00:24:51.542 --> 00:24:52.500
on the right hand side.

00:24:52.500 --> 00:24:54.340
It's logarithmic divergence.

00:24:54.340 --> 00:24:56.310
In three dimensions,
this doesn't diverge.

00:24:56.310 --> 00:24:59.030
In one dimension it
diverges big time.

00:24:59.030 --> 00:25:00.830
Two dimensions is the limit.

00:25:00.830 --> 00:25:02.710
There's a logarithmic
divergence.

00:25:02.710 --> 00:25:04.890
And if you do the math,
which is elementary,

00:25:04.890 --> 00:25:07.730
but I'm not doing it,
you find that the energy

00:25:07.730 --> 00:25:11.930
of the bound state depends
exponentially on minus 1

00:25:11.930 --> 00:25:13.450
over the attraction.

00:25:13.450 --> 00:25:16.430
So for infinitesimal
attraction, this

00:25:16.430 --> 00:25:18.870
turns to E to the
minus infinity.

00:25:18.870 --> 00:25:21.380
It's the weakest bound
state you can imagine,

00:25:21.380 --> 00:25:22.500
and this happens in 2D.

00:25:25.010 --> 00:25:29.160
OK, let's go from one particle
physics back to fermions.

00:25:29.160 --> 00:25:33.690
And let me now present to
you how Leon Cooper really

00:25:33.690 --> 00:25:38.185
found the key ingredients to
the long standing problem, "How

00:25:38.185 --> 00:25:40.680
do electrons pair in
a superconductor?"

00:25:40.680 --> 00:25:43.820
And he did the following.

00:25:43.820 --> 00:25:46.520
He made an artificial
simplification,

00:25:46.520 --> 00:25:49.240
which you can see is ingenious.

00:25:49.240 --> 00:25:50.690
He assumed the following.

00:25:50.690 --> 00:25:55.290
He just wanted to understand,
how do two electrons pair?

00:25:55.290 --> 00:25:58.060
But he simply assumed
that those two electrons

00:25:58.060 --> 00:26:00.480
are on top of a Fermi sea.

00:26:00.480 --> 00:26:03.790
So he pretty much said, "I
want to solve the problem where

00:26:03.790 --> 00:26:09.860
two electrons just scatter
through all available states

00:26:09.860 --> 00:26:14.910
and then figure out if an
infinitesimal attraction

00:26:14.910 --> 00:26:18.190
between those electrons
leads to binding."

00:26:18.190 --> 00:26:21.740
Of course, in the real world,
the electrons in the Fermi sea

00:26:21.740 --> 00:26:23.860
are identical to
those electrons,

00:26:23.860 --> 00:26:26.720
to those two special electrons,
and they're constantly

00:26:26.720 --> 00:26:27.700
exchanged.

00:26:27.700 --> 00:26:30.430
But he simply made
this artificial model.

00:26:30.430 --> 00:26:32.680
And then, of course,
we can immediately

00:26:32.680 --> 00:26:35.090
write down the
equivalent equation.

00:26:35.090 --> 00:26:38.850
It's exactly the same
formalism, except for when

00:26:38.850 --> 00:26:41.770
we integrate over
all energies here.

00:26:41.770 --> 00:26:44.090
We integrate, yes.

00:26:44.090 --> 00:26:48.020
We integrate over the
three-dimensional energy.

00:26:48.020 --> 00:26:53.120
But now, we integrate
only over a small region

00:26:53.120 --> 00:26:56.230
on top of the Fermi sea.

00:26:56.230 --> 00:26:58.310
And everything looks the same.

00:26:58.310 --> 00:27:01.830
We just have sometimes
subtract the Fermi energy.

00:27:01.830 --> 00:27:05.340
All energies are now
measured not relative to 0,

00:27:05.340 --> 00:27:08.400
but relative to
the Fermi energy.

00:27:08.400 --> 00:27:11.870
If you compare it to the
equation I just showed you,

00:27:11.870 --> 00:27:14.000
forcing the particle
bound state,

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:17.020
you pretty much see that
everything is the same,

00:27:17.020 --> 00:27:20.560
except for energies are measured
relative to the Fermi energy.

00:27:20.560 --> 00:27:24.340
And secondly, we're not
integrating from zero,

00:27:24.340 --> 00:27:25.420
as before.

00:27:25.420 --> 00:27:28.830
We start integrating
from the Fermi energy.

00:27:28.830 --> 00:27:33.760
And that means now, that in
this area of integration,

00:27:33.760 --> 00:27:37.860
the three-dimensional density
of states is constant,

00:27:37.860 --> 00:27:41.960
namely it's the density for
where the energy is the Fermi

00:27:41.960 --> 00:27:45.220
energy and can be pulled
out of the integral.

00:27:45.220 --> 00:27:47.640
And then we have the same
logarithmic divergence

00:27:47.640 --> 00:27:50.910
as we had in two dimensions.

00:27:50.910 --> 00:27:54.860
So therefore, the problem
of two electrons scattering

00:27:54.860 --> 00:27:58.040
on the surface of
the Fermi sea means

00:27:58.040 --> 00:28:00.890
that we have essentially
the same condition

00:28:00.890 --> 00:28:03.760
for the electrons as if they
would live in two dimensions.

00:28:07.580 --> 00:28:08.310
Question.

00:28:08.310 --> 00:28:11.030
If the world were
four-dimensional,

00:28:11.030 --> 00:28:13.960
and we would have
the same physics,

00:28:13.960 --> 00:28:17.870
we have two electrons on the
surface of the Fermi sea,

00:28:17.870 --> 00:28:21.320
would the physics of the two
electrons, in that regard,

00:28:21.320 --> 00:28:24.871
be 4 minus one dimension,
three dimension,

00:28:24.871 --> 00:28:26.120
or would it be two dimensions?

00:28:30.310 --> 00:28:33.190
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:28:33.190 --> 00:28:36.550
PROFESSOR: Well, that's
exactly the question.

00:28:36.550 --> 00:28:40.450
Let's assume you had
four spatial dimensions.

00:28:40.450 --> 00:28:43.690
For this kind of analysis,
it's the effective density

00:28:43.690 --> 00:28:46.550
of states on the Fermi surface.

00:28:46.550 --> 00:28:48.766
Now, two dimensional?

00:28:48.766 --> 00:28:49.910
Or is it three-dimensional?

00:28:52.666 --> 00:28:55.600
AUDIENCE: It should
be three, right?

00:28:55.600 --> 00:28:57.556
You remove one
dimension by restricting

00:28:57.556 --> 00:29:00.980
yourself the area
in the Fermi sea?

00:29:00.980 --> 00:29:06.645
PROFESSOR: It is, if you say
the particles have momentum

00:29:06.645 --> 00:29:10.630
on the Fermi surface, if
the Fermi surface fixes

00:29:10.630 --> 00:29:14.350
one momentum, and now they
have three different momenta.

00:29:14.350 --> 00:29:17.800
So in that sense, the motion on
the surface in four dimension,

00:29:17.800 --> 00:29:19.380
is three-dimensional.

00:29:19.380 --> 00:29:22.350
But, it was sort of a trick
question, to some extent,

00:29:22.350 --> 00:29:24.635
because here we have
reformulated everything

00:29:24.635 --> 00:29:26.730
with energy.

00:29:26.730 --> 00:29:31.240
And the answer is now, the
density of state is constant.

00:29:31.240 --> 00:29:34.440
It is the four-dimensional
density of states,

00:29:34.440 --> 00:29:37.790
but evaluated at
the Fermi energy.

00:29:37.790 --> 00:29:39.910
So therefore, no matter
in what dimensions

00:29:39.910 --> 00:29:43.370
you are, because you are
restricted to the Fermi sea,

00:29:43.370 --> 00:29:50.460
you integrate over energy with
a constant density of states.

00:29:50.460 --> 00:29:52.742
And if you pull the
constant density state out

00:29:52.742 --> 00:29:55.500
of the integral you have
a logarithmic divergence.

00:29:55.500 --> 00:29:58.890
And you pretty much
get the same answer.

00:29:58.890 --> 00:30:00.840
So, therefore the
physics in four dimension

00:30:00.840 --> 00:30:01.990
would be the same.

00:30:01.990 --> 00:30:05.960
It would be the fermions
which live on this Fermi

00:30:05.960 --> 00:30:09.980
surface would just
marginally pair.

00:30:09.980 --> 00:30:14.880
AUDIENCE: Can you explain
the reduction of dimensions?

00:30:14.880 --> 00:30:16.350
Where does [INAUDIBLE]

00:30:23.630 --> 00:30:26.740
PROFESSOR: Well, the motion,
you can see on the Fermi surface

00:30:26.740 --> 00:30:28.560
is n minus one dimension.

00:30:28.560 --> 00:30:30.970
But the energetic
analysis always

00:30:30.970 --> 00:30:33.240
uses a constant
density of state.

00:30:33.240 --> 00:30:34.810
And the constant
density of state

00:30:34.810 --> 00:30:37.880
is characteristic
for two dimensions.

00:30:37.880 --> 00:30:38.880
So you have both.

00:30:38.880 --> 00:30:41.350
If you analyze the
motion, yes, you

00:30:41.350 --> 00:30:43.670
have n minus one dimensions.

00:30:43.670 --> 00:30:46.260
But if you look at the
question of bound states,

00:30:46.260 --> 00:30:50.110
you encounter the same
situation as in two dimension,

00:30:50.110 --> 00:30:53.280
because the effective density
of states is constant.

00:30:57.510 --> 00:31:00.750
OK so with that, the
message I have for you is,

00:31:00.750 --> 00:31:03.510
Cooper pairing is a
single particle effect.

00:31:03.510 --> 00:31:06.755
A single particle trapped to
an arbitrarily weak potentially

00:31:06.755 --> 00:31:08.360
in two dimensions.

00:31:08.360 --> 00:31:10.500
And the only many-body
physics which

00:31:10.500 --> 00:31:12.380
allows those Cooper
pairs to form

00:31:12.380 --> 00:31:14.920
is, that you have
a Pauli blocking,

00:31:14.920 --> 00:31:17.490
that you have Fermi sea,
which prevents particles

00:31:17.490 --> 00:31:20.390
from going into
the deep Fermi sea.

00:31:20.390 --> 00:31:22.800
They stay on the surface,
and therefore, they

00:31:22.800 --> 00:31:24.210
form weak pairs.

00:31:24.210 --> 00:31:26.020
So the only many
body physics, which

00:31:26.020 --> 00:31:29.668
we need for that kind of
pairing is Pauli blocking.

00:31:29.668 --> 00:31:30.496
Mark.

00:31:30.496 --> 00:31:31.162
AUDIENCE: Sorry.

00:31:31.162 --> 00:31:35.150
Can you explain what is
ER in the previous slide?

00:31:35.150 --> 00:31:36.495
PROFESSOR: ER was the cutoff.

00:31:36.495 --> 00:31:38.800
We were cutting
off the potential

00:31:38.800 --> 00:31:41.580
at a short-- we didn't
use a delta potential,

00:31:41.580 --> 00:31:45.660
we used a square of l potential,
which extends out to R. And ER

00:31:45.660 --> 00:31:52.260
is the recoil energy associated
with R. Its 1 over R squared,

00:31:52.260 --> 00:31:54.800
with a few h bars and n to
give it the units of energy.

00:31:57.710 --> 00:31:58.680
Colin.

00:31:58.680 --> 00:32:01.650
AUDIENCE: If you
go back to that,

00:32:01.650 --> 00:32:05.143
I can imagine Taylor
expanding my density of states

00:32:05.143 --> 00:32:09.090
in any dimension
around Fermi energy.

00:32:09.090 --> 00:32:12.010
I'll always have my constant
term, and the first term is 3D,

00:32:12.010 --> 00:32:16.540
it's E to 1/2, or
some linear term.

00:32:16.540 --> 00:32:21.923
Doesn't that imply that
even if give the system

00:32:21.923 --> 00:32:25.787
any infinitesimal
amount of energy,

00:32:25.787 --> 00:32:31.580
that integral no
longer diverges and--

00:32:31.580 --> 00:32:32.540
PROFESSOR: No.

00:32:32.540 --> 00:32:35.000
The question of
divergence is robust.

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:38.010
Depends only on the leading
term and not on the expansion.

00:32:41.690 --> 00:32:43.190
If you have a
divergence you are not

00:32:43.190 --> 00:32:47.610
changing it by a
small correction term.

00:32:47.610 --> 00:32:50.990
Because a small correction
term is on top of unity.

00:32:50.990 --> 00:32:54.700
If you start with the
density of states at 0,

00:32:54.700 --> 00:32:57.020
which goes with
epsilon to some power,

00:32:57.020 --> 00:32:59.460
you have a different situation.

00:32:59.460 --> 00:33:01.530
You catch really the
physics by saying

00:33:01.530 --> 00:33:04.760
you take a constant
density of states here.

00:33:04.760 --> 00:33:09.840
Anyway, let me just go on and
say we should now figure out--

00:33:09.840 --> 00:33:11.370
and this is also
important when it

00:33:11.370 --> 00:33:16.090
comes to pairing-- which pairs
are the most important ones.

00:33:16.090 --> 00:33:18.040
And the message I
want to give you here,

00:33:18.040 --> 00:33:20.250
the pairs which are
most important one,

00:33:20.250 --> 00:33:22.990
on the ones which
have zero momentum.

00:33:22.990 --> 00:33:27.680
Because those pairs can scatter
to all states on the Fermi

00:33:27.680 --> 00:33:31.460
surface without violating
momentum conservation.

00:33:31.460 --> 00:33:36.080
However, if you have the total
momentum of the two particles

00:33:36.080 --> 00:33:39.080
which is non-0, they
can only scatter

00:33:39.080 --> 00:33:42.010
on the segment of the sphere.

00:33:42.010 --> 00:33:45.640
And you got already the message
that the higher the density

00:33:45.640 --> 00:33:49.410
of state, the better
it is for the binding.

00:33:49.410 --> 00:33:52.260
So therefore, the pairs
which have the largest

00:33:52.260 --> 00:33:55.740
binding energies will be the
one with total momentum zero.

00:33:59.800 --> 00:34:04.370
OK, now we go from
Cooper to BCS.

00:34:04.370 --> 00:34:07.250
Those three guys figured
out how they can now

00:34:07.250 --> 00:34:10.360
take the physics
described by Cooper,

00:34:10.360 --> 00:34:14.090
and really fold it into a
correct many-body formalism.

00:34:14.090 --> 00:34:17.280
In other words, not to
artificially have 2 fermions,

00:34:17.280 --> 00:34:19.560
which scatter, and there
is just the Fermi sea

00:34:19.560 --> 00:34:20.710
of the other ones.

00:34:20.710 --> 00:34:22.940
They are now treating
the two electrons,

00:34:22.940 --> 00:34:27.020
which scatter, on equal footing
with the whole Fermi sea.

00:34:27.020 --> 00:34:31.800
So, now we have democracy, all
electrons are created equal.

00:34:31.800 --> 00:34:35.449
So I want to derive for
you the BCS wavefunction

00:34:35.449 --> 00:34:38.520
in the way which was not the
way done by Bardeen, Cooper,

00:34:38.520 --> 00:34:41.060
Schrieffer, but it makes
an immediate analogy

00:34:41.060 --> 00:34:43.215
with Bose-Einstein condensation.

00:34:43.215 --> 00:34:46.770
, So what happens is you
could now have the idea--

00:34:46.770 --> 00:34:50.239
of course I'm very suggestive
in leading you to this idea--

00:34:50.239 --> 00:34:52.770
two fermions form a pair.

00:34:52.770 --> 00:34:57.060
And if the pairs both
condense, then each pair

00:34:57.060 --> 00:34:58.940
would be identical.

00:34:58.940 --> 00:35:01.260
So maybe we should
take our n particles,

00:35:01.260 --> 00:35:06.395
our n fermions-- n half spin
up, n spin down-- each of them

00:35:06.395 --> 00:35:07.890
should form a pair.

00:35:07.890 --> 00:35:10.910
So one and two forms a pair,
three and four forms a pair,

00:35:10.910 --> 00:35:11.860
and such.

00:35:11.860 --> 00:35:13.955
And then we see,
our wavefunction

00:35:13.955 --> 00:35:17.890
of identical fermion
pairs slash bosons is just

00:35:17.890 --> 00:35:19.800
the product of those pairs.

00:35:19.800 --> 00:35:22.666
But the pairing wavefunction,
the molecular wavefunction

00:35:22.666 --> 00:35:24.040
if you want, so
[INAUDIBLE], it's

00:35:24.040 --> 00:35:27.060
the same for all particles.

00:35:27.060 --> 00:35:30.030
So this is just like in the
Bose-Einstein condensate.

00:35:30.030 --> 00:35:32.720
We have a product state of n
times the same wavefunction.

00:35:32.720 --> 00:35:35.070
Here we have a product
state of n over two

00:35:35.070 --> 00:35:36.907
times the same
pairing wavefunction.

00:35:40.780 --> 00:35:44.650
We should anti-symmetrize
that's important.

00:35:44.650 --> 00:35:47.310
Now let us see what we got.

00:35:47.310 --> 00:35:50.710
Well, we describe everything
in second quantization.

00:35:50.710 --> 00:35:54.070
We use field operators
which create particles

00:35:54.070 --> 00:35:55.560
at a certain
position, and then we

00:35:55.560 --> 00:35:57.080
have the wavefunction
of the pairs

00:35:57.080 --> 00:36:00.160
to make sure they are created
in the right position.

00:36:09.980 --> 00:36:12.070
We transform everything
our operators

00:36:12.070 --> 00:36:16.040
and do Fourier transform.

00:36:16.040 --> 00:36:18.330
We go from operators
and positions space,

00:36:18.330 --> 00:36:20.310
to operators in momentum space.

00:36:20.310 --> 00:36:22.517
But now, it's just formalism.

00:36:22.517 --> 00:36:23.600
You can read up about it..

00:36:23.600 --> 00:36:25.891
But the important thing is
now I define a pair creation

00:36:25.891 --> 00:36:26.520
operator.

00:36:26.520 --> 00:36:29.910
This pair creation operator
creates one of those pairs.

00:36:29.910 --> 00:36:33.190
And what it does is it creates.

00:36:33.190 --> 00:36:37.000
We want to focus on the
pairs we zero momentum.

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:40.720
It forms a plain wave fermion
in the momentum state with minus

00:36:40.720 --> 00:36:43.620
k, with opposite
spin with plus k.

00:36:43.620 --> 00:36:46.450
So these are sort of two
opposite, plain waves

00:36:46.450 --> 00:36:47.540
with zero momentum.

00:36:47.540 --> 00:36:52.560
But now the leading factor
is the Fourier transform

00:36:52.560 --> 00:36:55.670
of this pairing wavefunction.

00:36:55.670 --> 00:36:58.210
So if you want to assume it's
a molecule or wavefunction,

00:36:58.210 --> 00:37:01.240
Fourier transformers, and
this is the leading factor.

00:37:01.240 --> 00:37:04.795
And with that definition, this
is now the creation operator

00:37:04.795 --> 00:37:06.975
of a molecule consisting
of two fermions.

00:37:10.230 --> 00:37:10.980
OK.

00:37:10.980 --> 00:37:15.290
So now, we can say, well
maybe a good idea of what

00:37:15.290 --> 00:37:19.100
describes our system
is now, so to speak,

00:37:19.100 --> 00:37:21.210
a Bose-Einstein
condensate, where

00:37:21.210 --> 00:37:24.530
we create n over two
pairs out of the vacuum.

00:37:27.290 --> 00:37:32.160
Well, first I want to show
you that this is actually

00:37:32.160 --> 00:37:34.080
the BCS wavefunction.

00:37:34.080 --> 00:37:37.380
Most people do not to use this
form for the BCS wavefunction,

00:37:37.380 --> 00:37:39.790
but I want to show you
mathematically identical

00:37:39.790 --> 00:37:41.530
the BCS wavefunction.

00:37:41.530 --> 00:37:45.670
But first I have to clarify is
that really a Bose-condensate?

00:37:45.670 --> 00:37:48.920
If I would have shown you this
equation without telling you

00:37:48.920 --> 00:37:54.170
anything about it, ya, this
looks -- n over 2 identical, b,

00:37:54.170 --> 00:37:56.460
boson-- Bosonic particles.

00:37:56.460 --> 00:37:58.260
But now we have to
be more careful.

00:37:58.260 --> 00:38:01.220
We have our definition
for the pairing operator.

00:38:01.220 --> 00:38:03.580
And now we can calculate.

00:38:03.580 --> 00:38:04.440
Are those bosons?

00:38:04.440 --> 00:38:06.070
Let's just look at
the communicator

00:38:06.070 --> 00:38:08.130
between b dega, b dega, bb.

00:38:08.130 --> 00:38:09.520
Yes fine fine.

00:38:09.520 --> 00:38:15.470
But now, the commutator
between b and b dega is not 1.

00:38:15.470 --> 00:38:19.220
It would be 1 if
the probability,

00:38:19.220 --> 00:38:24.360
that the population of one
of those plain waves k,

00:38:24.360 --> 00:38:27.380
is much, much
smaller than 1, then

00:38:27.380 --> 00:38:29.830
the commutator is full filled.

00:38:29.830 --> 00:38:35.920
But the population
of momentum states

00:38:35.920 --> 00:38:38.530
depends on the size of the pair.

00:38:38.530 --> 00:38:43.830
If the size is huge, you have
low lying momentum states,

00:38:43.830 --> 00:38:45.270
which have a huge population.

00:38:45.270 --> 00:38:49.530
If the size is small of
the pair, you can say,

00:38:49.530 --> 00:38:52.130
in a tightly-bound system,
particles have so much

00:38:52.130 --> 00:38:54.670
0 point energy that
every given momentum

00:38:54.670 --> 00:38:58.100
state has pretty
much 0 occupation.

00:38:58.100 --> 00:39:00.920
So in other words,
this criterion here,

00:39:00.920 --> 00:39:06.815
tells us that our
pairs are bosons if nk

00:39:06.815 --> 00:39:08.930
is much smaller than 1.

00:39:08.930 --> 00:39:13.350
But if nk is not smaller
than 1, then those pairs

00:39:13.350 --> 00:39:17.020
act out in a Fermionic way.

00:39:17.020 --> 00:39:20.120
And the criterion
happens exactly when

00:39:20.120 --> 00:39:23.090
the size of the pairs is
comparable to the particle

00:39:23.090 --> 00:39:25.060
spacing.

00:39:25.060 --> 00:39:27.560
So in other words,
what we have described

00:39:27.560 --> 00:39:30.440
with this wavefunction
is, we have a wavefunction

00:39:30.440 --> 00:39:32.410
which is a two
Bose-Einstein condensate

00:39:32.410 --> 00:39:33.460
for tightly bound pairs.

00:39:33.460 --> 00:39:35.320
That's what we expect.

00:39:35.320 --> 00:39:39.610
It still has this form,
but those pairs now

00:39:39.610 --> 00:39:42.780
feel the Fermi pressure.

00:39:42.780 --> 00:39:45.570
And therefore, this
is automatically

00:39:45.570 --> 00:39:46.905
taken account in the formalism.

00:39:46.905 --> 00:39:47.405
Colin

00:39:47.405 --> 00:39:48.280
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:39:50.632 --> 00:39:51.465
PROFESSOR: This one.

00:39:51.465 --> 00:39:53.890
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:39:53.890 --> 00:39:57.320
PROFESSOR:It's a commutator
not the anti-commutator.

00:39:57.320 --> 00:40:00.230
It's bb dega minus b dega b.

00:40:00.230 --> 00:40:02.720
I just want to be careful here
because, for fermions, you

00:40:02.720 --> 00:40:04.440
often use the anti-commutator.

00:40:04.440 --> 00:40:06.580
But I want to check
with these bosons,

00:40:06.580 --> 00:40:08.151
so I use the Bosonic,
the commutator,

00:40:08.151 --> 00:40:09.150
not the anti-commutator.

00:40:12.610 --> 00:40:15.260
Let me just show you
one thing real quick.

00:40:15.260 --> 00:40:20.870
Namely, that this wavefunction
is identical to the famous BCS

00:40:20.870 --> 00:40:22.830
wavefunction.

00:40:22.830 --> 00:40:26.860
Well, almost, not quite.

00:40:26.860 --> 00:40:30.040
You know that this
is a state which

00:40:30.040 --> 00:40:34.380
has n particles,
n over two pairs.

00:40:34.380 --> 00:40:36.250
Remember when we
talked about photons,

00:40:36.250 --> 00:40:40.640
we had Fock states with n
particles, with n photons.

00:40:40.640 --> 00:40:45.220
But we also had coherent states,
where alpha square was n.

00:40:45.220 --> 00:40:49.190
But this was sort of, the
classic coherent state.

00:40:49.190 --> 00:40:51.480
And this coherent
state could be expanded

00:40:51.480 --> 00:40:53.860
as a sum over Fock states.

00:40:53.860 --> 00:40:56.300
And one can now
say, to some extent,

00:40:56.300 --> 00:41:00.680
when it comes to certain
properties of light, n photons

00:41:00.680 --> 00:41:02.810
sometimes it's
important to distinguish

00:41:02.810 --> 00:41:04.970
whether it be a Fock
state or coherent state.

00:41:04.970 --> 00:41:06.540
But, for many
things, if you have

00:41:06.540 --> 00:41:09.337
n photons in the same
state, you can have a laser,

00:41:09.337 --> 00:41:10.920
then you have a
coherent state, or you

00:41:10.920 --> 00:41:12.470
have n photons in a cavity.

00:41:12.470 --> 00:41:14.500
And that may be similar.

00:41:14.500 --> 00:41:20.390
So let me show you what happens
when I take this Fock state,

00:41:20.390 --> 00:41:24.390
but construct what is now
the coherent state version.

00:41:24.390 --> 00:41:30.200
In the coherent state
version-- this here

00:41:30.200 --> 00:41:33.950
is a Fock state
with j particles--

00:41:33.950 --> 00:41:37.310
but now I take a
coherent superposition,

00:41:37.310 --> 00:41:39.395
and I've chosen my
factors such that I

00:41:39.395 --> 00:41:41.150
will get a coherent state.

00:41:41.150 --> 00:41:43.490
And indeed, I get
the coherent state.

00:41:46.770 --> 00:41:51.860
This is now sort of, what
the laser is for Fock state,

00:41:51.860 --> 00:41:55.320
is this coherent state for a
state with a specific Fermion

00:41:55.320 --> 00:41:56.290
number.

